{"title_page": "Colin Kolles", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Colin Kolles\n| image       = Colin Kolles 2009 1000km of Okayama.jpg\n| birthname   = C\u0103lin Colesnic\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = Kolles in 2009\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1967|12|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Timi\u0219oara]], Romania\n| nationality = Romanian / German\n| title       =\n| predecessor =\n| successor   =\n| residence   =\n| parents     =\n| spouse      =\n| children    =\n}}\n\n'''Colin Kolles''' (born C\u0103lin Colesnic<ref name=\"Puterea\">{{cite web|url=http://www.puterea.ro/sport/exclusiv_stomatologul_formulei_1_puterea_va_prezinta_povestea_lui_calin_col-15347.html|title=Stomatologul Formulei 1. \u201cPuterea\u201d v\u0103 prezint\u0103 povestea lui C\u0103lin Colesnic, singurul rom\u00e2n din Formula 1|publisher=Puterea|date=6 February 2011|language=Romanian}}</ref> 13 December 1967 in [[Timi\u0219oara]], [[Romania]]<ref name=\"Puterea\"/>) is a [[Romanians in Germany|Romanian-German]] former team principal and managing director of the [[Hispania Racing|Hispania Racing F1 Team]], previously holding a similar position at the team known under the names [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]], [[Midland F1 Racing|Midland]], [[Spyker F1|Spyker]] and [[Force India]] from 2005 to 2008. He was an advisor to [[Caterham F1]] and had  a part in the unsuccessful [[Forza Rossa Racing]] project.\n\n==Career==\nKolles, who lives in [[Ingolstadt]], is qualified as a [[dentist]] which was the family business. In 2000 he entered racing by establishing a team now known as [[Kodewa|ByKolles Racing]] with his father Romulus in the [[German Formula Three Championship]], and later in the [[Formula Three Euroseries]]. He was appointed as Managing Director of the [[Jordan Grand Prix]] team by its new owner, [[Alex Shnaider]], on 19 January 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.midland.gg/index.php?page=default/news&news=22|title=Midland Group website|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060906075750/http://www.midland.gg/index.php?page=default%2Fnews&news=22|archivedate=2006-09-06}}</ref>\n\nDespite receiving some criticism in 2005 for his \"hard-headed\" approach, Kolles kept his position as Managing Director of the team, presiding over the launch of the [[Midland F1 Racing|Midland]] M16 chassis before the [[2006 Formula One Season|2006 season]] began.<ref>[http://www.formula1.com/news/3967.html \"MF1 team boss Colin Kolles on 2006 and the new M16...\"].</ref> Following the team's takeover by Spyker and then [[Force India]], he remained as managing director.\n\nDespite running a Formula One team, Kolles has still been called upon to use his dentistry skills. Before the [[2005 Turkish Grand Prix]], he was forced to perform dental surgery on his driver [[Tiago Monteiro]], who was suffering from toothache that was severe enough to potentially keep him out of the race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/funny_old_game/4170862.stm|title=Jordan overcome teething troubles}}</ref> He also performed a similar procedure on Midland's other driver [[Christijan Albers]] at the [[2006 French Grand Prix]].\n\nIn November 2008, it was announced that Force India chairman [[Vijay Mallya]] was to take over the role of Team Principal for {{F1|2009}}, leaving Kolles without a major role in the team. He remained contracted to the team until 31 October 2009, when he resigned as a director.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kolles leaves Force India|publisher=[[Haymarket Group|Haymarket Publications]]|work=autosport.com|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/80000|date=2009-11-03|accessdate=2009-11-03}}</ref>\n\nKolles returned to Kodewa in 2009 where he fielded a pair of ex-works [[Audi R10]]s for sportscar stalwart [[Michael Krumm]], [[Charles Zwolsman Jr.|Charles Zwolsman Jr]], ex-single seater drivers Andrew Meyrick and [[Christian Bakkerud]], and sometime [[Formula One]] drivers [[Christijan Albers]] and [[Narain Karthikeyan]] in the [[Le Mans Series]] and [[24 Hours of Le Mans]].  He oversaw Kodewa'e.<ref>{{cite news|last=Elizalde|first=Pablo|title=Carabante takes over Campos team|publisher=[[Haymarket Group|Haymarket Publications]]|work=autosport.com|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/81606|date=2010-02-19|accessdate=2010-02-19}}</ref> He left the position in December 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.f1ofakind.com/2011/12/colin-kolles-leaves-hrt-for-2012.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-08-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105022347/http://www.f1ofakind.com/2011/12/colin-kolles-leaves-hrt-for-2012.html |archivedate=2012-11-05 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, it emerged that Kolles had previously tried to blackmail [[Mercedes-Benz]] Motorsport boss [[Toto Wolff]] after he had allegedly recorded Wolff making negative remarks about the [[Mercedes-Benz in Formula One|Mercedes F1 Team]]'s management. The two allegedly settled the matter privately.<ref>http://grandprix247.com/2013/07/17/ex-hrt-boss-kolles-tried-to-blackmail-wolff-for-money/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.bykolles.com/ Kolles racing team official website]\n\n{{Jordan Grand Prix}}\n{{Midland F1 Racing}}\n{{Spyker F1}}\n{{Force India F1}}\n{{Hispania Racing F1 Team}}\n{{Caterham F1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kolles, Colin}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]] \n[[Category:Sportspeople from Timi\u0219oara]]\n[[Category:German motorsport people]]\n[[Category:Romanian motorsport people]] \n[[Category:Romanian expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:Formula One people]]\n[[Category:Spyker]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Germany]]\n[[Category:Sports car racing team owners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Colin Kolles\n| image       = Colin Kolles 2009 1000km of Okayama.jpg\n| birthname   = C\u0103lin Colesnic\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = Kolles in 2009\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1967|12|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Timi\u015foara]], Romania\n| nationality = Romanian / German\n| title       =\n| predecessor =\n| successor   =\n| residence   =\n| parents     =\n| spouse      =\n| children    =\n}}\n\n'''Colin Kolles''' (born C\u0103lin Colesnic<ref name=\"Puterea\">{{cite web|url=http://www.puterea.ro/sport/exclusiv_stomatologul_formulei_1_puterea_va_prezinta_povestea_lui_calin_col-15347.html|title=Stomatologul Formulei 1. \u201cPuterea\u201d v\u0103 prezint\u0103 povestea lui C\u0103lin Colesnic, singurul rom\u00e2n din Formula 1|publisher=Puterea|date=6 February 2011|language=Romanian}}</ref> 13 December 1967 in [[Timi\u015foara]], [[Romania]]<ref name=\"Puterea\"/>) is a [[Romanians in Germany|Romanian-German]] former team principal and managing director of the [[Hispania Racing|Hispania Racing F1 Team]], previously holding a similar position at the team known under the names [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]], [[Midland F1 Racing|Midland]], [[Spyker F1|Spyker]] and [[Force India]] from 2005 to 2008. He was an advisor to [[Caterham F1]] and had  a part in the unsuccessful [[Forza Rossa Racing]] project.\n\n==Career==\nKolles, who lives in [[Ingolstadt]], is qualified as a [[dentist]] which was the family business. In 2000 he entered racing by establishing a team now known as [[Kodewa|ByKolles Racing]] with his father Romulus in the [[German Formula Three Championship]], and later in the [[Formula Three Euroseries]]. He was appointed as Managing Director of the [[Jordan Grand Prix]] team by its new owner, [[Alex Shnaider]], on 19 January 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.midland.gg/index.php?page=default/news&news=22|title=Midland Group website|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060906075750/http://www.midland.gg/index.php?page=default%2Fnews&news=22|archivedate=2006-09-06}}</ref>\n\nDespite receiving some criticism in 2005 for his \"hard-headed\" approach, Kolles kept his position as Managing Director of the team, presiding over the launch of the [[Midland F1 Racing|Midland]] M16 chassis before the [[2006 Formula One Season|2006 season]] began.<ref>[http://www.formula1.com/news/3967.html \"MF1 team boss Colin Kolles on 2006 and the new M16...\"].</ref> Following the team's takeover by Spyker and then [[Force India]], he remained as managing director.\n\nDespite running a Formula One team, Kolles has still been called upon to use his dentistry skills. Before the [[2005 Turkish Grand Prix]], he was forced to perform dental surgery on his driver [[Tiago Monteiro]], who was suffering from toothache that was severe enough to potentially keep him out of the race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/funny_old_game/4170862.stm|title=Jordan overcome teething troubles}}</ref> He also performed a similar procedure on Midland's other driver [[Christijan Albers]] at the [[2006 French Grand Prix]].\n\nIn November 2008, it was announced that Force India chairman [[Vijay Mallya]] was to take over the role of Team Principal for {{F1|2009}}, leaving Kolles without a major role in the team. He remained contracted to the team until 31 October 2009, when he resigned as a director.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kolles leaves Force India|publisher=[[Haymarket Group|Haymarket Publications]]|work=autosport.com|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/80000|date=2009-11-03|accessdate=2009-11-03}}</ref>\n\nKolles returned to Kodewa in 2009 where he fielded a pair of ex-works [[Audi R10]]s for sportscar stalwart [[Michael Krumm]], [[Charles Zwolsman Jr.|Charles Zwolsman Jr]], ex-single seater drivers Andrew Meyrick and [[Christian Bakkerud]], and sometime [[Formula One]] drivers [[Christijan Albers]] and [[Narain Karthikeyan]] in the [[Le Mans Series]] and [[24 Hours of Le Mans]].  He oversaw Kodewa'e.<ref>{{cite news|last=Elizalde|first=Pablo|title=Carabante takes over Campos team|publisher=[[Haymarket Group|Haymarket Publications]]|work=autosport.com|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/81606|date=2010-02-19|accessdate=2010-02-19}}</ref> He left the position in December 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.f1ofakind.com/2011/12/colin-kolles-leaves-hrt-for-2012.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-08-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105022347/http://www.f1ofakind.com/2011/12/colin-kolles-leaves-hrt-for-2012.html |archivedate=2012-11-05 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, it emerged that Kolles had previously tried to blackmail [[Mercedes-Benz]] Motorsport boss [[Toto Wolff]] after he had allegedly recorded Wolff making negative remarks about the [[Mercedes-Benz in Formula One|Mercedes F1 Team]]'s management. The two allegedly settled the matter privately.<ref>http://grandprix247.com/2013/07/17/ex-hrt-boss-kolles-tried-to-blackmail-wolff-for-money/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.bykolles.com/ Kolles racing team official website]\n\n{{Jordan Grand Prix}}\n{{Midland F1 Racing}}\n{{Spyker F1}}\n{{Force India F1}}\n{{Hispania Racing F1 Team}}\n{{Caterham F1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kolles, Colin}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]] \n[[Category:Sportspeople from Timi\u0219oara]]\n[[Category:German motorsport people]]\n[[Category:Romanian motorsport people]] \n[[Category:Romanian expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:Formula One people]]\n[[Category:Spyker]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Germany]]\n[[Category:Sports car racing team owners]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Timi\u0219oara(viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colin_Kolles"}
{"title_page": "Staci Keanan", "text_new": "{{short description|American attorney and Actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Stacy Keenan\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| birthname       = Anastasia Love Sagorsky\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1975|06|06|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place     = [[Devon, Pennsylvania]], US\n| other_names     = {{Plainlist|\n* Anastasia Sagorsky\n* Staci Keanan\n* Anastasia Birtwhistle\n}}\n| alma_mater      = [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]]<br>[[Southwestern Law School]]\n| occupation      = Actress (1987\u20132010)<br>Attorney (2013\u2013present)\n| spouse          = {{marriage|Guy Birtwhistle|2017|}}\n}}\n\n'''Stacy Keenan''' (born '''Anastasia Love Sagorsky''' on June 6, 1975)<ref name=\"filmref\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/21/Staci-Keanan.html|title=Staci Keanan Biography (1975-)|website=Filmreference.com|accessdate=March 7, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Calbar\">{{cite web|title=The State Bar of California: Attorney Search|url=http://members.calbar.ca.gov/fal/member/detail/292053|website=calbar.ca.gov|publisher=The State Bar of California|accessdate=January 1, 2018}}</ref> is an American [[deputy district attorney]] and former [[actor|actress]]. Keenan is best known for portraying the role of Nicole Bradford on the [[NBC]] sitcom ''[[My Two Dads]]'', from 1987 to 1990, and as Dana Foster on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]/[[CBS]] sitcom ''[[Step by Step (TV series)|Step by Step]]'', from 1991 to 1998.\n\n==Early life==\nKeenan was born in [[Devon, Pennsylvania]] (near [[Philadelphia]]), the daughter of Jacqueline (n\u00e9e Love) and Irv Sagorsky, a car salesman.<ref name=filmref/><ref name=\"likes having\">Kim, Jae-Ha. [http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CSTB&p_theme=cstb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB36E8867362019&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM \"Actress likes having '2 Dads'\"], ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', November 17, 1989.</ref><ref name=\"J obit\">[http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PI&s_site=philly&p_multi=PI&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=129CE5D9BA75BE78&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM Obituary for Jacqueline Love Sagorsky], ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]'', July 30, 2009.</ref> She has a sister, Pilar.<ref name=\"J obit\" />\n\n==Career==\n===Acting===\nAt age five, she began modeling and appeared in print, radio, and television advertisements, including the voice of [[My Little Pony]] and television commercials for [[Burger King]] and [[Hershey's Kisses]]. As a youth, Keanan moved with her mother and sister to [[New York City]], where she changed her name to \"Staci Love\" and began appearing in [[summer stock theatre|summer stock]]. She made her credited television debut in the 1987 miniseries ''[[I'll Take Manhattan (miniseries)|''I'll Take Manhattan]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20097658,00.html|title=For Staci Keanan of TV's My Two Dads, Hollywood Can Be a Two-Faced Town |last1=Blessing|first1=Angela |last2=Holmstrom|first2=Rick |date=November 23, 1987 |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |accessdate=September 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 12, shortly after she moved with her family to [[Los Angeles]], she was cast as Nicole Bradford in the TV series ''[[My Two Dads]]''. The series ran from 1987 to 1990. During the 1990-91 season, she co-starred in the short-lived series ''[[Going Places (U.S. TV series)|Going Places]]'' with [[Alan Ruck]], [[Heather Locklear]], and [[Hallie Todd]]. The following year, Keanan was cast as Dana Foster in the TV series ''[[Step by Step (TV series)|Step by Step]]'' which aired from 1991 to 1998. By 1997 Keanan had changed her name from ''Staci'' to ''Stacy.''<ref>Podcast: [http://blog.wtfthepodcast.com/2008/02/10/wtf-the-podcast-cont-again.aspx 'Keanan, Stacy. Interview with Brian Castro.']{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''from'' [4:24\"], ''IMDB listing misspelled''. WTF? the Podcast. FX Show, Orlando. January 2008. Retrieved on October 24, 2010.</ref>\n\nKeanan had roles in the short ''Stolen Poem'' (2004) and the films ''Hidden Secrets'' (2006), and ''Death and Cremation'' (2010) with [[Brad Dourif]], [[Jeremy Sumpter]], and [[Daniel Baldwin]]. In 2009 Keanan appeared in ''Holyman Undercover'',<ref name=filmref /> and in 2010 she appeared in a cameo in ''[[You Again]]'' with ''Step By Step'' castmates [[Christine Lakin]] and [[Patrick Duffy]]. She also co-starred in the 2009 film ''Sarah's Choice''.\n\n===Law===\nKeanan received her undergraduate degree from [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]]. She then attended [[Southwestern Law School]] and was admitted to the [[State Bar of California]] in 2013. She currently practices law under her given name, Anastasia Sagorsky, in the Los Angeles area.<ref name=\"Calbar\" /> In 2014, Keanan worked as a prosecutor in the [[Riverside County, California|Riverside County]] District Attorney's Office who handles felony cases involving violent crime or death.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.riversidecountybar.com/Documents/Magazine-2014/Riverside-Lawyer-Magazine-volume-64-5-May-2014.pdf |title=The Inland Empire\u2013Southwestern Law School Connection |magazine=Riverside Lawyer |date=May 2014 |page=14}}</ref> By 2019, Keanan became a Deputy District Attorney in the [[Los Angeles County District Attorney]]'s office.<ref>{{cite new |url=http://da.lacounty.gov/media/news/man-sentenced-killing-77-year-old-woman-hit-and-run |title=Man Sentenced for Killing 77-Year-Old Woman in Hit-and-Run |work=Los Angeles County District Attorney's Office |date=August 16, 2019 |first=Paul |last=Eakins}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn February 11, 2017, Keanan married actor and producer Guy Birtwhistle.<ref>{{cite web|title='My Two Dads' Star Staci Keanan: Where Is She Now?|url=http://extratv.com/2014/08/23/my-two-dads-star-staci-keanan-where-is-she-now/|website=Extra|publisher=[[Extra (U.S. TV program)|Extra]]|accessdate=November 13, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Film roles\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Lisa (1990 film)|Lisa]]''\n| Lisa\n| Alternative title: ''Candlelight Killer''\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''Skooled''\n|\n| Short film\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''Ski Hard''\n| Annie Meyers\n| Alternative titles: ''Downhill Willie'', ''Ski Nuts''\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''The Red Coat''\n| Mary\n| Short film\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Nowhere (film)|Nowhere]]''\n| Ever\n| Credited as Stacy Keanan<ref>Film clip: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C4amsKBgLv8 'FILM \"NOWHERE\" CAST (1997)'] ''onscreen credits'' [1.43\"-1.47\"] ''as \"Stacy Keanan\".''</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/19970606235453/http://www.flf.com/nowhere/castcrew/index.html Nowhere (1997)] ''Cast and Crew'' at FLF.com (circa 1997 via [[Wayback Machine]].) Retrieved November 26, 2010.</ref>\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''Stolen Poem''\n| Jamie\nCredited as Stacy Keanan\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''Hidden Secrets''\n| Rachel Wilson\n| Credited as Stacy Keanan\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Sarah's Choice]]''\n| Denise\n| Credited as Stacy Keanan<ref>[[:File:Sarah's Choice.jpg|''Sarah\u2019s Choice DVD cover'']] ''DVD cover image''  Wikipedia.org. Retrieved October 24, 2010.</ref>\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Holyman Undercover]]''\n| Carmen\n| Credited as Stacy Keanan\n\n\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[You Again]]''\n| Dana\n| Credited as Stacy Keanan\n| \n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Death and Cremation]]''\n| Becky Weaver\n|Credited as Stacy Keanan \n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Television roles\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\